title: Triangle Velo Winter Ace Speedway Races
January Mountain Bike Marathon
description: Start off your 2014 season with the 7th annual January Mountain Bike Marathon at North Carolina’s original trail destination, Governor’s Creek. The mountain bike-training ride will be a cross-country mountain bike ride of approximately 42 miles. Riders will do one 6-mile lap around Governor’s Creek, head out for a 30-mile loop on paved and dirt roads, and return for a final 6-mile circuit on the trail. The average January high temperature is 52 and the average low is 29. In the event of threatening weather, please check the event website for the latest ride information.
course:
This is a training event on trails and roads. Free Pizza and a few prizes will be given away in a random drawing afterwards. Riders will be scored and assigned a placing. All Classes will start at the same time and be scored in the categories below. Use this event for early season training. This ride is longer than a normal XC race and it could be very cold. 

The middle portion of the course will be on lightly traveled, paved and dirt roads that are open to vehicle traffic. No traffic control will be provided. Participants must obey all state traffic regulations. Riders will need to dress accordingly for the weather and pace and feed themselves accordingly for the longer distance. Expect a first place finishing time of around 2 1/2 hours. Riders could take up to 4 hours or more to complete. Be Prepared for Anything.

description: VeloSports Racing will be hosting the Wheel Ride for Asheville as a part of the Mountain Sports Festival on Sunday March 25, 2014 at 9am departing from Carrier Park in Asheville, NC.  The Wheel Ride has been an integral part of the Western North Carolina cycling scene for six years as the Wheel Ride for Food benefiting Meals on Wheels. Hot Doggett 100
description:
Thinking about Hot Doggett 2014? Here's a short preview: We will again be based on the beautiful Mars Hill University campus. The roads, which were heavily damaged by summer storms prior to the 2013 event, are well on the way to full restoration. We plan to use our normal routes for both the Doggett Mountain Challenge 100 mile ride and the Devils Fork Metric.

We heard from riders that we should offer a shorter ride as well. So for 2014 we are going to add a 60k (37.5 mile) ride. While it doesn't have the climbs of Doggett Mountain, Devil's Fork or Sam's Gap, it will provide a nice challenge of the mountains of Madison County in a shorter distance.

After eight years with a manual way of tracking rider times, we are moving to a chip-based timing system for quicker and more accurate results. Comments in our post ride survey revealed that it's important to our riders to know what their times were with precision.

New this year! We are offering a special promotion for racing and recreational bike clubs - clubs with six or more riders will receive a rebate of $7 per rider. So if 10 members of a club participate, the club will receive a check for $70! Be sure to list your bike club affiliation when you register.

Want to register early? Registration for the July 12, 2014 event is now open on Active.com! We know some riders like to plan their season schedules at the start of the year so we hope you will take advantage of this opportunity to register when you want to.

Remember, the Hot Doggett offers on-campus accommodation, seven fully supported rest stops, awesome SAG support, free post-ride showers, post ride meal, great "swag bags" including a commemorative t-shirt and the opportunity to purchase a 2014 Hot Doggett cyclist jersey.

We hope to see you July 12, 2014 for the ninth annual Hot Doggett 100.

title: Mars Hill Cycling Camp
description:
Get fast or stay at home! Mars Hill Cycling announces its third annual summer cycling camp, July 13-18, 2014.  We are once again ready to rip your legs off and elevate your game. We’ll train your brain too—with elite level tactics and race proven secrets to success. Come sharpen fitness and fine tune race strategy before you tackle one of the region’s premier races: The French Broad Cycling Classic on July 18-20. This year the FBCC will be the third stop on the Southeast Regional Series. If there’s one race in the SE that you must attend, this is it. And we will make sure you’re better prepared than the competition. Visit our FACEBOOK PAGE (Mars Hill Cycling Camp) to learn more about last year’s camp and stay updated on this year’s developments.

All campers are encouraged to compete in the French Broad Cycling Classic on the weekend at the end of camp. You will have the opportunity to race as a team wearing official Mars Hill University team jerseys. The camp will specifically focus on the time trial, climbing, and criterium skills/tactics you’ll need to have an awesome race. We’ll preview courses during the week and come up with a plan of attack. Pre-race strategy and tactics will be followed by post-race reviews of each race. A great opportunity to put into practice specific knowledge learned during the week and receive immediate feedback from coaches afterward.
course: Find some of the courses we rode last year on the event webpage. We may mix it up some and also offer even longer days to more experienced riders. The highlight of camp is the ascent of Mt. Mitchell, the highest peak in the eastern US. http://marshillcycling.com/summer-camp/
notes:
WHERE: Camp will be based at Mars Hill University’s beautiful campus nestled in the heart of the Blue Ridge Mountains. The college provides immediate access to an amazing network of lightly traveled roads, including extended climbs, rolling terrain, and flat/fast rides along the river. Situated in Madison County (“The Jewel of the Blue Ridge”) Mars Hill’s neighbors include the Blue Ridge Parkway, Mt. Mitchell State Park, Pisgah National Forest, the Appalachian Trail, and the French Broad River. Mars Hill is just 18 miles north of vibrant Asheville, NC.

WHEN: Drop off: Sunday, July 13th: 2-3pm. Pick Up: Friday, July 18th: 1pm.

WHO: Aspiring racers ages 10-collegiate. Cyclists will be grouped based on experience, ability, and skill level. All cyclists must have prior group riding experience (racing isn’t required) and a current USA Cycling license. Parents are welcome.
directions:
Mars Hill University
100 Athletic Street
Mars Hill,  NC 28754

Directions to Camp: Our location is Dogwood Hall. From I-26 take exit 11. Go left at the stop sign and back over the interstate. Climb the hill to the first light at Main Street. Then cross over Main Street, descending hill through campus and making first left onto Dormitory Rd. Then take first right and follow to the last building on the road, Dogwood Hall.

title: Ride to the Rock
description: The 25-Mile Bike event begins at 7:30 AM just outside the park entrance. This is a beautiful yet challenging bike course. The route travels 22 miles, starting east on 64/74A, turns left onto Bills Creek Road by the Library, left again onto Buffalo Creek Road by Dalton’s Store and eventually merges into Buffalo Shoals Road along Lake Lure’s eastern shore. It re-enters Route 64/74A with a right turn back to Chimney Rock Village where a left turn into the park entrance begins the last 3 miles straight up to Chimney Rock.
course: 25 Mile course with the last 3 miles up Chimney Rock Park at a 7% grade
notes: Riders must sign the USA Cycling waiver.  Riders can purchase a one-day license for $10 on-site if they would like the accident medical coverage, but this is optional.

title: Bookwalter Binge
description: The BB Charity Gran Fondo is a bike ride in which cyclists will ride a challenging 86 or 30 mile course. The course will be marked, and a follow car will be on route. There will be four aid stations in the 86 time route, and one in the 30 mile route. There will also be 3 timed mountain climbing sections for those that wish to compete during the ride. The aid stations will the staffed by volunteers handing out snacks, sports drinks, and water, and some stations will have volunteer bike mechanics. There will be a rolling road block for the first 5 miles, and intersections that are particularly dangerous will have crossing guards. Participants will be able to enjoy the colorful fall foliage and have a chance to experience the hospitality and charm of Black Mountain and Asheville. Participants will also be able to ride and converse with past, present, and future cycling celebrities, who will join the ride as guides and guests.
course:
Course options are 82, 30 and 10 miles in length.  You can click on the following links to view the course maps:

82 mile option: http://ridewithgps.com/routes/3381294
30 mile option: http://ridewithgps.com/routes/3381249
registration:
All riders can pre-register online at USA Cycling.  Registration fees will go up on July 1st, so take advantage of the early bird registration discount.   Please donate to Trips for Kids WNC when you register.   There will be a prize package for the person who donates the most funds to the organization.  

Trips for Kids WNC provides bike riding opportunities to children from local area schools by organizing after school bike clubs. The organization also trains club volunteers and provides insurance, bikes, and helmets to the clubs. After school bike clubs allow elementary and middle school age children in Western North Carolina to ride mountain bikes around their schools and experience other bike-outing field trips. Many of the children involved in these programs do not have bicycles at home and have no access to safe riding areas. Furthermore, North Carolina has the 11th highest childhood obesity rate in the country. These bike riding experiences provide kids with healthy exercise, a chance to experience nature, and the simple joy of coasting downhill.

ALL JUNIORS 16 AND UNDER RIDE FREE!
notes: There are three timed segments on the 82 mile route.
